ncounters</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/J003026/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The main aim of the post doctoral fellowship is to disseminate the findings of a PhD study of disabled people?s healthcare encounters.There are two strands of findings.&amp;nbsp; The first concerns the nature of the disabling barriers in the NHS and their implications for disabled people.These findings will be disseminated to healthcare professionals through articles in the relevant practitioner journals&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; and through the development of an e-learning interactive training resource.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The second set of findings offers a fresh understanding of disability and impairment. These suggest impairment is an aspect of embodiment which requires the individual to act on and through the body. So impairment becomes a form of embodied doing, a doing&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; always enmeshed in multiple social relations. Conceiving impairment thus has the potential to contribute to debates about how to theorise disability. To realise this potential, three articles will be submitted to the relevant peer review journals.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The main ethical requirement of this project is the need for vigilance to protect the anonymity of the participants in the original research study and to maintain the integrity of the interview data.&lt;br />&lt;br />&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2014-05-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2012-01-16</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>96352</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>NHS: barriers to equal treatment</gtr:description><gtr:form>A magazine, newsletter or online publication</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>55FE0384-427C-45CB-915E-703AD348E2C6</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Article in Disability Now, February 2012 



Aimed at disabled people, this article described PhD research findings which suggested that despite equalities legislation, some NHS policies and practice meet the needs of people who are ill - but not of those who are disabled. It gave examples of some of the access barriers disabled people face. It was explained that while these barriers rarely stopped disabled people using the NHS, they often caused them unnecessary emotional upset, inconvenience and sometimes had a physical and/or economic cost. A description was also given of how the research findings have been used as the basis of an e-learning package to help healthcare professionals remove disabling barriers. An article for disabled people describing research findings on disability access barriers in the NHS

